This appendix collects the hints and sketched solutions for the problems in the algebraic geometry and set theory chapters.
Each entry names its problem; consult the corresponding chapter for the full statement.

# Affine varieties

*Real affine varieties are a single vanishing locus.*

_Hint._ Squares are nonnegative.

_Solution._ If $`V = \mathbb{V}(I)` with $`I = (f_1, \dots, f_m)` (as usual there are finitely many polynomials since $`\mathbb{R}[x_1, \dots, x_n]` is Noetherian) then we can take $`f = f_1^2 + \dots + f_m^2`.

*Complex varieties can't be empty.*

_Hint._ This is actually an equivalent formulation of the Weak Nullstellensatz.

_Solution._ Let $`I` be an ideal, and let $`\mathfrak{m}` be a maximal ideal contained in it.
(If you are worried about the existence of $`\mathfrak{m}`, it follows from Krull's theorem.)
Then $`\mathfrak{m} = (x_1 - a_1, \dots, x_n - a_n)` by the Weak Nullstellensatz.
Consequently, $`(a_1, \dots, a_n)` is the unique point of $`\mathbb{V}(\mathfrak{m})`, and hence this point is also in $`\mathbb{V}(I)`.

*Hilbert's Nullstellensatz from the weak form (the Rabinowitsch trick).*

_Hint._ Use the weak Nullstellensatz on $`n+1` dimensions.
Given $`f` vanishing on everything, consider $`x_{n+1}f - 1`.

_Solution._ The point is to check that if $`f` vanishes on all of $`\mathbb{V}(I)`, then $`f \in \sqrt I`.

Take a set of generators $`f_1, \dots, f_m`, in the original ring $`\mathbb{C}[x_1, \dots, x_n]`; we may assume it's finite by the Hilbert basis theorem.

We're going to do a trick now: consider $`S = \mathbb{C}[x_1, \dots, x_n, x_{n+1}]` instead.
Consider the ideal $`I' \subseteq S` in the bigger ring generated by $`\{f_1, \dots, f_m\}` and the polynomial $`x_{n+1} f - 1`.
The point of the last guy is that its zero locus does not touch our copy $`x_{n+1} = 0` of $`\mathbb{A}^n` nor any point in the "projection" of $`f` through $`\mathbb{A}^{n+1}` (one can think of this as $`\mathbb{V}(I)` in the smaller ring direct multiplied with $`\mathbb{C}`).
Thus $`\mathbb{V}(I') = \varnothing`, and by the weak Nullstellensatz we in fact have $`I' = \mathbb{C}[x_1, \dots, x_{n+1}]`.
So $$`1 = g_1 f_1 + \dots + g_m f_m + g_{m+1} \left( x_{n+1} f - 1 \right).`
Now the hack: *replace every instance of $`x_{n+1}` by $`\frac 1f`*, and then clear all denominators.
Thus for some large enough integer $`N` we can get $$`f^N = f^N(g_1 f_1 + \dots + g_m f_m)`
which eliminates any fractional powers of $`f` in the right-hand side.
It follows that $`f^N \in I`.

# Bonus: Bézout's theorem

*Completing the proof of Bézout's theorem.*

_Solution._ From the exactness, $`h_I(d) = h_I(d - k) + h_{I + (f)}(d)`, and it follows that $$`\chi_{I + (f)}(d) = \chi_I(d) - \chi_I(d - k).`
Let $`m = \dim \mathbb{V}_+(I) \ge 1`.
Now $`\dim \mathbb{V}_+(I + (f)) = m - 1`, so writing $`c_{\text{new}} = \deg (I + (f))` we have $$`\frac{\deg (I + (f)) \, d^{m-1} + \dots}{(m-1)!} = \frac{1}{m!} \left( \deg I \, (d^m - (d - k)^m) + \text{lower order terms} \right)`
from which we read off $$`\deg (I + (f)) = \frac{(m-1)!}{m!} \cdot k \binom m1 \deg I = k \deg I`
as needed.

*USA TST 2016/6.*

_Hint._ You will need to know about complex numbers in Euclidean geometry to solve this problem.

_Solution._ In complex numbers with $`ABC` the unit circle, it is equivalent to solving the two cubic equations $$`\begin{aligned} (p - a)(p - b)(p - c) &= (abc)^2 (q - 1/a)(q - 1/b)(q - 1/c) \\ 0 &= \prod_{\text{cyc}} (p + c - b - bcq) + \prod_{\text{cyc}} (p + b - c - bcq) \end{aligned}`
in $`p` and $`q = \overline p`.
Viewing this as two cubic curves in $`(p, q) \in \mathbb{C}^2`, by Bézout's theorem it follows there are at most nine solutions (unless both curves are not irreducible, but one can check the first one cannot be factored).
Moreover it is easy to name nine solutions (for $`ABC` scalene): the three vertices, the three excenters, and $`I`, $`O`, $`H`.
Hence the answer is just those three triangle centers $`I`, $`O` and $`H`.

# Morphisms of varieties

*Projective varieties are locally affine.*

_Hint._ Use the standard affine charts.

*An affine variety isomorphic to an irreducible projective variety is a point.*

_Hint._ Examine the global regular functions.

_Solution._ If they were isomorphic, we would have $`\mathcal{O}_V(V) \cong \mathcal{O}_W(W)`.
For irreducible projective varieties, $`\mathcal{O}_W(W) \cong \mathbb{C}`, while for affine varieties $`\mathcal{O}_V(V) \cong \mathbb{C}[V]`.
Thus we conclude $`V` must be a single point.

*The punctured plane is not affine.*

_Hint._ Assume $`f` was an isomorphism.
Then it gives an isomorphism $`f^\sharp \colon \mathcal{O}_V(V) \to \mathcal{O}_X(X) = \mathbb{C}[x, y]`.
Thus we may write $`\mathcal{O}_V(V) = \mathbb{C}[a, b]`, where $`f^\sharp(a) = x` and $`f^\sharp(b) = y`.
Let $`f(p) = q` where $`\mathbb{V}(a, b) = \{q\}`.
Use the definition of pullback to prove $`p \in \mathbb{V}(x, y)`, contradiction.

_Solution._ Assume for contradiction there is an affine variety $`V` and an isomorphism $`f \colon X \to V`.
Then taking the pullback we get a ring isomorphism $$`f^\sharp \colon \mathcal{O}_V(V) \to \mathcal{O}_X(X) = \mathbb{C}[x, y].`
Now let $`\mathcal{O}_V(V) = \mathbb{C}[a, b]` where $`f^\sharp(a) = x`, $`f^\sharp(b) = y`.
In particular, we actually have to have $`V \cong \mathbb{A}^2`.

Now in the _affine_ variety $`V` we can take $`\mathbb{V}(a)` and $`\mathbb{V}(b)`; these have nonempty intersection since $`(a, b)` is a maximal ideal in $`\mathcal{O}_V(V)`.
Call this point $`q`, and let $`p` be a point with $`f(p) = q`.

Then $$`0 = a(q) = (f^\sharp a)(p) = x(p)`
and so $`p \in \mathbb{V}(x) \subseteq X`.
Similarly, $`p \in \mathbb{V}(y) \subseteq X`, but this is a contradiction since $`\mathbb{V}(x, y) = \varnothing`.

# Sheaves and ringed spaces

*A sheaf equals its sheafification.*

_Solution._ Because the stalks are preserved by sheafification, there is essentially nothing to prove: both sides correspond to sequences of compatible $`\mathcal{F}`-germs over $`U`.

*Skyscraper sheaf.*

_Hint._ The stalk is $`R` at points in the closure of $`\{p\}`, and $`0` elsewhere.

*The support of a global section is closed.*

_Hint._ Show that the complement $`\{ p \mid [s]_p = 0 \}` is open.

# Localization

*Localizing $`\mathbb{Z}/2016\mathbb{Z}`$ away from $`60`$.*

_Solution._ One should get $`A[1/60] = \mathbb{Z}/7\mathbb{Z}`.

*Injectivity of localizations.*

_Hint._ Consider zero divisors.

_Solution._ If and only if $`S` has no zero divisors.

*Alluding to local rings.*

_Hint._ Only one!
(A proof is given a few chapters later.)

*A ring local at every prime need not be a domain.*

_Hint._ No.
Use a product ring.

_Solution._ Take $`A = \mathbb{C} \times \mathbb{C}`, or more generally a product of two or more integral domains.

